{
  "slug": "2025-oscar-nominations-snubs-surprises-and-wtfs",
  "title": "2025 Oscar Nominations: Snubs, Surprises, and WTFs",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2025-01-23",
  "runtimeMin": 97,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins react to the 97th Academy Award nominations before 8 a.m., then game out a two-film Best Picture race between Emilia Perez and The Brutalist. Emilia Perez lands 13, the second-most in Oscar history and the most ever for an international feature; The Brutalist gets 10 and a well-timed AI story; I'm Still Here crashes Best Picture; and Challengers gets shut out of score. They also tally their four-months-early Oscar bet (a 30-30 tie) before Sean's interview with Flow director Gints Zilbalodis.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Snubs, surprises, and WTFs",
      "note": "the stories behind the board",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Emilia Pérez",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "13 nominations, second-most in Academy history and the most ever for an international feature. The hosts read it as chalk, not shock, but note the internet reaction has been sharply negative and that Sean still can't find anyone willing to mount a filmmaking defense of it. It also occupies the Netflix slot, and Netflix's big-number nominees (The Irishman, Maestro, Roma) keep falling short."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Brutalist",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "10 nominations and the biggest threat to Emilia Perez. The hosts spend a long stretch on the Red Shark News story about AI use in the film: an editor using a tool to correct Adrien Brody's Hungarian pronunciation, and a consultant using Midjourney for the end-credits architectural sketches. They call it a well-executed, old-school campaign smear that probably won't dent Best Picture but could hurt Brody in Best Actor."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wicked",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "10 nominations, mostly craft, plus Cynthia Erivo and Ariana Grande. Sean argues the backlighting and color grading make the practical sets look worse than they are, costing it a real Production Design case; its best shot below the line is Costume Design."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Complete Unknown",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "8 nominations, more than either host predicted. James Mangold sneaking into Best Director (matching his DGA nod) is the surprise; they see the crowd-pleasing Dylan biopic slowly creeping up as the throwback 'Oscar movie' of the field."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "6 nominations, but the six that matter: picture, director, actress, supporting actor, screenplay, editing. Amanda has had it as her Best Picture pick since August, and the hosts build the ranked-choice case for it as the film almost nobody puts last."
        },
        {
          "title": "I'm Still Here",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The morning's biggest surprise, in for Best Picture with Fernanda Torres also landing Best Actress 27 years after her mother's Central Station nod. The hosts credit the Golden Globe win and a sustained Brazilian campaign for pushing it past the film they'd been holding the slot for."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nickel Boys",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The Best Picture nod Sean predicted and wasn't sure would land. He wonders how much of A24's awards muscle shifted from this to The Brutalist; getting in despite no VOD or streaming shows people sought it out in screening rooms."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Substance",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Five nominations, which the hosts call insane for a body-horror movie. Demi Moore has taken over the Best Actress race from Mikey Madison, and they float The Substance as a plausible No. 2 on Emilia Perez ballots for the go-for-it international voter."
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclave",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Now relegated to a nice-year congratulations. Edward Berger missing Best Director confirms to Sean that the late Conclave-surge take is dead, though Isabella Rossellini's first-ever nomination lands in Supporting Actress."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune: Part Two",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Five below-the-line nominations (cinematography, production design, sound, visual effects) plus Best Picture, fewer than the first film. Denis Villeneuve missing Best Director again isn't a shock but still stings the hosts, who'd like a popular, top-tier filmmaker represented there."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sing Sing",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "In for Adapted Screenplay but shut out of Best Picture, and Clarence Maclin missed Supporting Actor, the performance Sean preferred over Colman Domingo's. He blames a bungled release strategy and thinks a traditional fall rollout would have changed the story."
        },
        {
          "title": "Challengers",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The snub the hosts kept hearing about all morning: no Original Score nod despite the Golden Globe win. Part of a total Academy cold shoulder to Luca Guadagnino, whose Queer also went home empty."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hard Truths",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Completely shut out. Sean skipped I'm Still Here to see it and was bowled over; Marianne Jean-Baptiste was his pick to win Best Actress, and her absence is the loss he keeps circling back to."
        },
        {
          "title": "September 5",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A slightly strange Original Screenplay nominee, competent and unflashy in a category the hosts prize for its transgressive picks. Sean's interview with writer-director Tim Fehlbaum runs the following week. He calls it a 'lady's seven,' a good movie he isn't sure why he's arguing about."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nosferatu",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Four craft nominations (cinematography, production design, costume design, makeup and hairstyling) but no Best Picture, delivered one at a time in a way that had the hosts texting each other 'is it really happening?'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Apprentice",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sebastian Stan in for Best Actor (for this, not for A Different Man, the performance both hosts preferred) and Jeremy Strong in Supporting Actor. The hosts fold it into the read that this Academy is honoring films responsive to the current American moment."
        }
      ]
    },
